{"title_page": "Secrets of Life", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Secrets of Life\n| image          = Secrets of Life poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[James Algar]]\n| producer       = [[Ben Sharpsteen]]\n| writer         = James Algar \t\n| narrator       = [[Winston Hibler]]\n| starring       = \n| music          = [[Paul Smith (film and television composer)|Paul Smith]]\n| cinematography = [[William A. Anderson]]<br>Arthur Carter<br>[[Jack Couffer]]<br>Robert H. Crandall<br>Murl Deusing<br>Fran William Hall<br>Claude Jendrusch<br>Stuart V. Jewell<br>George MacGinitie<br>Nettie MacGinitie<br>Tilden W. Roberts<br>Donald L. Sykes<br>[[Roman Vishniac]]\n| editing        = Anthony Gerard \n| studio         = [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1956|11|6}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Secrets of Life''''' is a 1956 American [[documentary film]] written and directed by [[James Algar]]. The documentary follows the changing world of nature, the sky, the sea, the sun, planets, insects and volcanic action. The documentary was released on November 6, 1956, by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/500433/Secrets-of-Life/|title=Secrets of Life (1956) - Overview - TCM.com|work=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C03E6DA1230E23BBC4951DFB767838D649EDE|title=Movie Review -   Secrets of Life - Screen: 'Secrets of Life'; Disney True-Life Adventure, at Sutton, Observes Nature With Zest - NYTimes.com|publisher=|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe fourth in Walt Disney's True-Life Adventure series, the 1956 film ''Secrets of Life'' features previously rarely-seen film footage of nature's \"behind-the-scenes\" goings-on that play a huge role in making the planet what it is. From bees to ants and the flora and fauna surrounding us, ''Secrets of Life'' reveal a sometimes startling glimpse into nature's wonders that we often take for granted. Accompanied by remarkably appropriate musical selections, viewers find themselves mesmerized by the metamorphosis of air-borne seeds into glorious plants and flowers with the help of time-lapse photography.\n\nBees are seen as they go about the non-stop business of pollination, giving adage to the saying \"busy as a bee.\" Ants are shown in their various classifications, from workers to warriors to the regal \"queen.\" Countless protozoa are viewed in a single drop of water as the voice-over describes their role in the \"big picture\" of unseen nature.\n\nThe close-ups provide an intimacy which gives these oft-neglected organisms a \"face.\" The folks at Disney once again bring subjects to life that heretofore were neglected.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0049733|Secrets of Life}}\n\n{{True Life Adventures}}\n\n[[Category:1956 films]]\n[[Category:Disney documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:1950s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Algar]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nature]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Ben Sharpsteen]]\n\n\n{{nature-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Secrets of Life\n| image          = Secrets of Life poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[James Algar]]\n| producer       = [[Ben Sharpsteen]]\n| writer         = James Algar \t\n| narrator       = [[Winston Hibler]]\n| starring       = \n| music          = [[Paul Smith (film and television composer)|Paul Smith]]\n| cinematography = [[William A. Anderson]]<br>Arthur Carter<br>[[Jack Couffer]]<br>Robert H. Crandall<br>Murl Deusing<br>Fran William Hall<br>Claude Jendrusch<br>Stuart V. Jewell<br>George MacGinitie<br>Nettie MacGinitie<br>Tilden W. Roberts<br>Donald L. Sykes<br>[[Roman Vishniac]]\n| editing        = Anthony Gerard \n| studio         = [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1956|11|6}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Secrets of Life''''' is a 1956 American [[documentary film]] written and directed by [[James Algar]]. The documentary follows the changing world of nature, the sky, the sea, the sun, planets, insects and volcanic action. The documentary was released on November 6, 1956, by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/500433/Secrets-of-Life/|title=Secrets of Life (1956) - Overview - TCM.com|work=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C03E6DA1230E23BBC4951DFB767838D649EDE|title=Movie Review -   Secrets of Life - Screen: 'Secrets of Life'; Disney True-Life Adventure, at Sutton, Observes Nature With Zest - NYTimes.com|publisher=|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe fourth in Walt Disney's True-Life Adventure series, the 1956 film Secrets of Life features previously rarely-seen film footage of nature's \"behind-the-scenes\" goings-on that play a huge role in making the planet what it is. From bees to ants and the flora and fauna surrounding us, Secrets of Life reveal a sometimes startling glimpse into nature's wonders that we often take for granted. Accompanied by remarkably appropriate musical selections, viewers find themselves mesmerized by the metamorphosis of air-borne seeds into glorious plants and flowers with the help of time-lapse photography.\n\nBees are seen as they go about the non-stop business of pollination, giving adage to the saying \"busy as a bee.\" Ants are shown in their various classifications, from workers to warriors to the regal \"queen.\" Countless protozoa are viewed in a single drop of water as the voice-over describes their role in the \"big picture\" of unseen nature.\n\nThe close-ups provide an intimacy which gives these oft-neglected organisms a \"face.\" The folks at Disney once again bring subjects to life that heretofore were neglected.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0049733|Secrets of Life}}\n\n{{True Life Adventures}}\n\n[[Category:1956 films]]\n[[Category:Disney documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:1950s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Algar]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nature]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Ben Sharpsteen]]\n\n\n{{nature-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gildir", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:: Italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secrets_of_Life"}
